02f1d411-e548-4742-9356-2d66e28d9791.047c372c-4b19-4e59-87c5-6d066fac5cad.description=
Adds a list of flow variables to the local context. The variables are available in the current flow and its child flows.

Inputs\:
    keyNames - The names of the flow variables to add, separated by "delimiter".
    myValues - The values to assign to the flow variables, separated by "delimiter".
    delimiter - The delimiter that separates the key names and the values from the "keyNames" and "myValues" input strings.

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the value of "myValue" input field.

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.

Notes\:
1. If the number of variable names is greater than the number of variable values, the value of each variable will be the value of "myValues" input field.
2. If the number of variable names is less than the number of variable values, the additional variable values will be discarded.
02f1d411-e548-4742-9356-2d66e28d9791.06d87699-ea87-410f-a7a9-4e72edb87199.description=
This operation checks whether a string matches another string, using a specific matching rule. The "toMatch" input is the string that is checked for matching the "matchTo" expression. 

Inputs\:
    matchType - The type of match to perform.
Valid values\: Exact Match, Contains, Contains Once, Does Not Contain, Match All Words, Match No Words, Regex (The values are not case sensitive)
Default value\: Exact Match
    toMatch - The string that is checked for matching.
    matchTo - The string to match against.
Example\: If "matchType" is “RegEx”, the "matchTo" input is a regular expression such as\: ^-?\d+(([\.,]\d+)?)+$. 
    ignoreCase - Specifies whether to ignore case when matching or not.
Valid values\: False, True
Default value\: False

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. It contains the string "Matches" if the "toMatch" string matches the "matchTo" string. Otherwise, it contains the string "Does Not Match".  

Responses\:
    success - The operation completed as stated in the description.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

02f1d411-e548-4742-9356-2d66e28d9791.4ee0ea98-b55e-4662-97cb-0bccc23053a6.description=
Useful Op to keep a running results.
Takes a string input (resultText) and appends this to a global context key of "runningResults". As a result, the context key whose name is in the keyName input will be appended with the string from the input resultText.

Input Parameters\:
keyName - name of context key to append to
resultText - string input to append
delimiter - (leave blank for none) the delimiter to put between what is already in keyName before appending resultText

Responses\:
success - assigned the context variable

Returns\:
The value of the context variable it appended to.

Context\:
runningResults

Scriptlet Example\:
currentResults \= scriptletContext.get("runningResults");

if (currentResults \=\= null) {
   currentResults \= resultText;
} else {
   currentResults +\= resultText;
}


scriptletContext.putGlobal("runningResults", currentResults);

02f1d411-e548-4742-9356-2d66e28d9791.a8b959a5-62e8-49f3-b098-dc8855dc54af.description=
This operation iterates through a list of values. It is not recommended to modify the value of the "list" and "separator" inputs during the iteration process.

Inputs\:
    list - The list to iterate through.
    separator - A delimiter separating the list elements.
Default value\: ‘,’ (comma) 

Results\:
    resultString - The current list element (if the response is "has more").

Responses\:
    has more - Another value was found in the list and it has been returned.
    no more - The iterator has gone through the entire list. This response is returned once per list iteration.  A subsequent call to the List iterator operation restarts the list iteration process.
    failure - The operation completed unsuccessfully.

Note\:
   The position of the iterator in the list is tracked by each step's unique identifier. Therefore, you can simultaneously iterate through the same list from multiple steps.
02f1d411-e548-4742-9356-2d66e28d9791.b60c072f-25b2-4490-8d77-b4b1dc5adacd.transition.description=has more 02f1d411-e548-4742-9356-2d66e28d9791.c1d93c6e-4d90-45cc-ae9c-89201138b9d1.transition.description=automation failure 02f1d411-e548-4742-9356-2d66e28d9791.da769d9c-e0d8-4d99-9902-ac25727f132d.description=
Retrieves the cell data with specified row index and column index in an Excel document. 
XLS, XLSX and XLSM formats are supported. 

Inputs\:
    excelFileName - The absolute path to the new Excel document.
Examples\: c\:\temp\test.xls
    worksheetName - The name of Excel worksheet. 
Default value\: Sheet1
    hasHeader - If Yes, then the first row of the document is expected to be the header row. 
Valid values\: yes, no
Default value\: Yes
    firstRowIndex - The index of the first row in the Excel worksheet, including the header row.
Default value\: 0
    rowIndex - A list of row indexes.
Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25
Default Value\: from the index of the first row  to the index of the last row in the Excel worksheet.
    columnIndex - A list of column indexes.
Examples\: 1\:3, 10, 15\:20,25
Default value\: from 0 to the index of the last column in the Excel worksheet.
    rowDelimiter - The delimiter used to separate the rows of the returnResult.
Default value\: | (pipe)
    columnDelimiter - The delimiter used to separate the columns of the returnResult.
Default value\: , (comma)

Results\:
    returnResult - This is the primary output. Returns the cell data retrieved from Excel document.
    header - A delimited list of column names of data being returned if hasHeader is set to Yes. 
    rowsCount - The number of the rows returned.
    columnsCount - The number of the columns returned.

Responses\:
    success - The cell data was retrieved successfully.
    failure - Failed to retireve the cell data.

Notes\:
1. All the index inputs are 0 based.
2. Observed that in some Excel worksheet, the first couple of rows are used for title. So added firstRowIndex input.
3. For the indexes in rowIndex input that is less than the first data row index or greater than the last row index in the worksheet, the operation trims those row indexes.
4. For the indexes in columnIndex input that is less than 0 or greater than the last column index in a row, the operation trims those column indexes.
5. The cell data with fraction format shows as double value in returnResult.
